{"key":"processedPost-15941382","value":{"id":15941382,"first":15936993,"last":19216800,"when":1331651009,"utime":"03/13/12 06:03 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Strains will stay alive up to 5 years with this method. What I don't know is how long a strain will stay viable on a petri dish, in cold storage, compared to a culture slant. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />Many of my best commercial strains are 20 to 30 years old, so they'll stay alive in culture slants far longer than 5 years.<br /><br />A petri dish has a very thin layer of nutrient, and this dries out rapidly.&nbsp; A slant has more media with less surface area exposed to evaporation, plus less air space.&nbsp; This means they can last for years.&nbsp; In addition, plastic petri dishes respirate somewhat, while glass slant tubes do not.<br />RR","title":"Re: Cold storage of culture slants vs petri dishs","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}